-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for IRON_HIR_EXPR_ENUM_CONSTRUCT.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02's collect_mono_enums_node
-- walker was literally the collection pass for monomorphized enum
-- types -- it walked every AST looking for enum construction sites.
-- The walker's if/elif/else layout bug caused the same pass to crash
-- on programs that used enum constructors inside control flow. Enum
-- construct is therefore both a producer (the bug hid here) and a
-- sink (the bug crashed here) for the Phase 37-02 SIGSEGV. Phase 66
-- added PROT-04 blind-cast rewrites for Iron_EnumConstruct (see
-- tests/integration/enum_construct_reinterpret.iron) and
-- -Werror=switch-enum. This canary is the per-node-kind runtime
-- regression net complementing those structural guards.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Iron_EnumConstruct carries
--   { span, kind, enum_type_ref, variant_name, args[], arg_count }
-- Walker cases that fail to recurse into args[] silently drop the
-- variant payload from the lowered LIR, producing a zero-initialized
-- payload at runtime. Walker cases that fail to recurse into
-- enum_type_ref mis-dispatch to the wrong enum type when multiple
-- enums share a variant name.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. Complements enum_construct_reinterpret.iron (Phase 66-03
-- PROT-04 fixture) with a minimal 3-variant enum and match-over-
-- variants integration. CI integration: runs in both Debug and
-- Release via Phase 66-04's build-and-test-release job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- enum_construct is the
-- exact node kind the Phase 37-02 motivating bug walked, so it
-- carries the most bisection weight for any future walker regression.

enum Color {
  Red(Int),
  Green(Int),
  Blue(Int),
}

func Color.intensity() -> Int {
  match self {
    Color.Red(v)   -> return v
    Color.Green(v) -> return v * 2
    Color.Blue(v)  -> return v * 3
  }
  return 0
}

func main() {
  val r = Color.Red(10)
  val g = Color.Green(10)
  val b = Color.Blue(10)
  var total = 0
  total = total + r.intensity()    -- 10
  total = total + g.intensity()    -- 20
  total = total + b.intensity()    -- 30
  println("total: {total}")
}
